{{! /freestyle/insights — patterns observed in the documented sequence archive }}

<div class="hero hero-sm">
  <div>
    {{#if navigation.breadcrumbs}}
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      {{#each navigation.breadcrumbs}}
        {{#if href}}<a href="{{href}}">{{label}}</a> <span class="breadcrumb-sep">/</span> {{else}}<span>{{label}}</span>{{/if}}
      {{/each}}
    </nav>
    {{/if}}
    <h1>{{page.title}}</h1>
    {{#if page.intro}}<p class="hero-subtitle">{{page.intro}}</p>{{/if}}
  </div>
</div>

<div class="wrapper">

  <p>
    These tables describe patterns within a documented archive of competitive freestyle
    sequences: which tricks recur, which ones link others together, and which players
    showed the widest range. They describe the archive on hand, not the sport as a whole.
    Unfamiliar terms are explained in the
    <a href="/freestyle/glossary">freestyle glossary</a>.
  </p>

  {{! ═══ Vocabulary ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Vocabulary</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="section-intro">Which tricks and modifiers appear most across the documented record.</p>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Commonly Used Tricks</h3>
    <p class="section-intro">Tricks that recur across the documented record, with their current canonical ADD. An illustrative selection, not an exact frequency ranking.</p>
    <div class="records-table-wrap">
      <table class="records-table records-table-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Trick</th>
            <th class="col-adds">ADD</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.mostUsed}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{name}}</td>
            <td class="col-adds">{{adds}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Most Used Modifiers</h3>
    <p class="section-intro">How many canonical tricks carry each modifier. This is dictionary usage, not competitive frequency.</p>
    <div class="records-table-wrap">
      <table class="records-table records-table-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="col-rank">#</th>
            <th>Modifier</th>
            <th>Type</th>
            <th class="col-num">Tricks</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.mostUsedModifiers}}
          <tr>
            <td class="col-rank">{{rank}}</td>
            <td>{{name}}</td>
            <td class="detail-muted">{{type}}</td>
            <td class="col-num">{{count}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Connector Tricks</h3>
    <p class="section-intro">Tricks that commonly act as connectors between others in a sequence, with their current canonical ADD. Illustrative, not a ranking.</p>
    <div class="records-table-wrap">
      <table class="records-table records-table-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Trick</th>
            <th class="col-adds">ADD</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.connectors}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{name}}</td>
            <td class="col-adds">{{adds}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  {{! ═══ Sequence Structure ═════════════════════════════════════════════════ }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Sequence Structure</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="section-intro">How tricks connect into chains across the documented sequences.</p>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Example Transitions</h3>
    <p class="section-intro">Illustrative examples of how one trick can follow another: a high-difficulty rotational opener resolving to a stable closer, or walking tricks connecting mid-chain. These are examples of the pattern, not measured frequencies.</p>
    <div class="records-table-wrap">
      <table class="records-table records-table-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>From</th>
            <th>To</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.transitions}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{from}}</td>
            <td>{{to}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Example High-ADD Chains</h3>
    <p class="section-intro">Illustrative high-ADD chains. Each ADD is the sum of the current canonical ADD values of the tricks in the chain, shown as canonical arithmetic, not a recovered historical competition score. These are examples, not a ranking of the hardest sequences ever performed.</p>
    <div class="records-table-wrap">
      <table class="records-table records-table-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="col-adds">ADD</th>
            <th class="col-adds">Length</th>
            <th>Sequence</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.notableSequences}}
          <tr>
            <td class="col-adds">{{adds}}</td>
            <td class="col-adds">{{length}}</td>
            <td class="col-message">{{sequence}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  {{! ═══ Player Diversity ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Player Diversity</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="section-intro">Some competitors are noted for the breadth of distinct tricks they bring to a run, spreading difficulty across many different elements rather than repeating a few. The per-player trick counts that once ranked this drew on a sequence corpus that is not reproducible from committed sources, so they are not shown.</p>
  </section>

  {{! ═══ Archive Notes ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Archive Notes</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="section-intro">What this data is, and what it is not.</p>
    <p>
      The sequence tables draw on a documented archive of Sick3 format sequences, where each trick
      carries a mechanically verifiable ADD value. This page is an educational interpretation of that
      archival sample, not a complete or reproducible census. Sick3 submissions are one slice of
      competitive freestyle, so these are patterns within the sample rather than conclusions about the
      sport overall.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frequencies count how often a trick appears in those sequences. Modifier tricks such as
      pixie, ducking, and spinning have no fixed standalone ADD; they are counted by mention only.
      Some sequence attributions were recovered from surrounding context rather than a direct
      record, so individual rows carry varying confidence. The modifier-usage table above is a
      separate, live count from the trick dictionary and updates with the dictionary itself.
    </p>
    <p>
      These statistics derive from a historical Sick3 analysis corpus preserved as editorial
      research. The underlying sequence export is no longer fully reproducible from currently
      available source files, so these values are presented as archival findings rather than
      live-generated statistics.
    </p>
  </section>

</div>
